<br>
Anyway, I thought T3 was good, and a credit to the series. They manage to interject a little more humor than the first two, but I don't think it was overdone. Of course, the action and special effects are well done, and they did a good job presenting the TX as a different kind of terminator. She strikes me as being kind of a hybrid between the T-101s and the T-1000. She has a metal skeleton with a shape-shifting facade over it, which was a neat idea. Where the T-1000 was more of an assassin type, she's a battle bot. They advance the plot a little more and for the most part do a good job of keeping the apocolyptic overtones from the T2 intact. Over all, it was a good movie, and I look forward to the next one.<br>
<br>
Just to be interesting, I'll toss in a few of the things that weren't as great. The tie-in to T2 was a little weak. Ah-nold says that judgement day wasn't avoided, it was just postponed, but they never show any link between the Skynet of T2 and the Skynet of T3 (a military undertaking). So basically, two totally separate events had the exact same outcome in the future. Hmm. Not a big deal, but I felt they could have done better in that department.<br>
<br>
Other than that, it has it's typical share of hollywood silliness, like when the leading lady exclaims, &quot;there's my father's plane! I've trained on it!&quot;. Several people could be heard snickering in the theater when she said that. It's just a classic example of the isn't-that-convenient syndrome, where all the major characters miraculously know how to fly planes, hack computers, and shoot grenade launchers with perfect aim. Again, a minor mistake that nearly *every* action movie makes.<br>
<br>
There was also the whole thing with the computer virus. I won't say too much, but let's just say that all the geeks in the audience were cringing at the way hollywood makes absurd scenarios where virus can take over stoves, burn your eggs benedict, and steal your soul. But I tried not to let that bother me too much because you have to realize that hardly anything is realistically portrayed in action movies. If an RPG explodes 10 feet away, you will, most likely, be killed. Cranes can't drive that fast, nor can they stay upright if their mast is out to the side, smashing through buildings at 60 mph. You can't run through an active particle accelerator. These are all obvious physics blunders, but that's never really bothered me. It's not realistic, but it makes for better visuals. I'll take the virus thing with the same grain of salt, then. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=simanmistrunner>SimanMistrunner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 754<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/9/03 1:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1727.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Terminator 3</span><hr size=1> I liked it.  I agree that they needed to get a better explanation on how the new skynet developed and why the old skynet was irrelevant.<br>
