<br>
The problem with T3 is the same problem I've found with Alien 3 and Alien Ressurection:  it takes a remarkable director to breath life into an established concept.<br>
<br>
James Cameron wrote and directed T1 and T2 and he expanded the frontiers of CGI with his efforts to create the morphing T-1000 from T2 (the groundwork for which was performed when Cameron made the Abyss and the &quot;water tentacle&quot;, an often underrated movie).  Likewise, Cameron took the concept of the first Alien movie (brilliantly directed by Ridley Scott, a God in his own right) and updated the entire concept in a very entertaining manner (with the introduction of the Colonial Marines).<br>
<br>
Linda Hamilton (the actress who played Sarah Connor) was approached to reprise her role for T3, however she stated that &quot;without James Cameron at the helm, the life of the Terminator series is gone&quot;.  She stated this despite the fact that there is no love lost between herself and James Cameron (they were married and went through a fairly bitter divorce) and the fact that she's not exactly in high demand and could use the work.<br>
<br>
I'm skeptical that T4 will introduce anything that challenges the audience...but I'll see it anyhew simply because Arnie rules.<br>
<br>
